The Future of Chronic Wound Treatment

We are a team from TU Dresden participating in iGEM 2022

What is iGEM?

The International Genetically Engineered Machine (iGEM) is a student competition dedicated to the advancement of synthetic biology, interdisciplinary cooperation and education. It involves thousands of participants and hundreds of teams from all over the world every year. Our team is composed of 13 members from 6 different countries - Italy, Belarus, USA, Lithuania, Russia, and Germany - with students from all three master programs of the Center for Molecular and Cellular Bioengineering (CMCB) and from Informatik, Medieninformatik, and the Hochschule für Bildende Künste.

Synthetic Biology

What is Synthetic Biology?

Synthetic biology consists in the design and construction of biological modules, systems, and machines, such as enzymes, genetic circuits, and cells, or the re-design of existing biological systems.

The element that distinguishes synthetic biology from traditional molecular and cellular biology is the focus on engineering principles. Synthetic biology sees biological entities as hardware to repurpose to solve specific problems.

The Problem

Chronic Wounds

The increase in life expectancy science has brought into existence in the last decades represents an extraordinary feat for the whole of humanity. At the same time, overabundance of food and an excessive caloric intake have become the norm in affluent societies. These achievements have brought consequences with them, such as a rise in age-related maladies and diabetic and obesity-dependent comorbidities, among which are enumerated various types of chronic wounds.

At the same time, the overreliance on antibiotics has produced ever more dangerous antibiotic-resistant bacterial strains, which are especially prevalent in clinical settings where individuals suffering from chronic wounds may be put at risk of infection.

Chronic wounds and the emergence of antibiotic resistance pose serious challenges for us and for future generations and must be tackled to insure prosperity.

Our Solution

We intend to use a hydrogel, which will be used as a platform for administering bacteriophages and the human growth factors to chronic wounds. We have selected a multi-arm star polyethylene glycol (starPEG) polymer as the main constituent for the hydrogel dressing. This polymer offers several benefits, such as elevated drug loading capacity and biocompatibility, and can be easily and extensively functionalized.

We will incorporate heparin, a natural glycosaminoglycan, to slow down the release of our growth factors. A slower release will reduce the risk of inducing tumorigenesis in the tissue under treatment. We also plan to render the hydrogel bioresponsive through the addition of short protease-specific peptides that can be cleaved by endogenous proteases, thus effectively coupling the physiological state and need of the wound to the administration of our therapeutics.

We aim to create new tools to express therapeutic proteins in yeast and demonstrate the efficacy of our hydrogel as a drug delivery platform.

This will facilitate the work of future research teams endeavoring to solve the challenges posed by chronic wounds. Moreover, we hope to raise awareness about the dangers of chronic wounds and antibiotic resistance.

Phage Therapy

To combat the presence of antimicrobial-resistant bacteria, we aim to entrap a phage cocktail within a hydrogel drug-release platform that can be used to treat infected wounds. We intend to establish reliable protocols for the preparation, storage, viability, and safety of hydrogels as phage carriers, as these aspects are still understudied. Moreover, we would like to conduct proof of concept experiments to demonstrate that it is possible to target gram-positive and negative bacteria using the same hydrogel as the delivery system for therapeutic bacteriophages.

Growth Factors

We plan to conduct growth factor therapy using our hydrogel platform to stimulate the healing of chronic wounds. We will use yeast cells as biofactories for the synthesis of human growth factors. We want to promote the use of this model organism in the iGEM community by developing a yeast shuttle vector for MoClo assembly and expression of heterologous DNA sequences and by expanding the registry of genetic parts available for the iGEM community - for example, by screening for high-efficiency yeast signal peptides for secretion of therapeutic proteins.
